properties.name: Ohio River
properties.description:
There is reason to believe that the Cherokee considered the Ohio River to be the northern limit of their territory around the year 1715. The southern Ohio River drainage basin in modern-day Kentucky and West Virginia was far from the heartland of Cherokee settlements and used primarily as hunting grounds. This territory was by no means the sole proprietorship of the Cherokees, however. The Kentucky hunting grounds overlapped with the claims of a neighboring people, the Shawnees, resulting in tense and sometimes violent encounters up until the Cherokees’ eventual cession of the lands in a series of treaties between 1768–1775.

By the mid-seventeenth century, a loose alliance network of two to four thousand Algonquin speakers identifying collectively as Shawnee occupied the territory stretching from the Cumberland River to the Ohio Valley. In the 1670s and 1680s, in response to the violent encroachment of the expansionist Haudenosaunee from the north and armed slaver societies from the south, the Shawnee dispersed across eastern North America in dozens of bands in search of trade and alliances. By the 1680s, the Ohio Valley was largely depopulated (Lakomaki 2014, 24–34).

According to French maps from the period, however, at least some Shawnees remained along the Cumberland River in the vicinity of modern Nashville. By around 1710, these remaining Cumberland Shawnees became embroiled in a war with the much larger Chickasaw and Cherokee peoples and they too gradually withdrew. By 1714, a French trader named Charleville reported that the retreat from the Nashville area was already underway. A 1720 map by Hermann Moll depicts “Savanah Old Settlement” at the mouth of the Cumberland River, suggesting that the Shawnee had by that date completely removed from the area. Mooney gives the date of the Shawnee expulsion as about 1715 (Mooney 1975 [1900], 38).

With the removal of the Shawnees from the Cumberland River, the Cherokee and Chickasaw both claimed dominion over the newly vacated territory in modern Middle Tennessee and Western Kentucky. In light of the territory that they would later cede in the 1760s and 1770s, the Cherokee considered their territorial claim to extend to the Ohio River as far upstream as the mouth of the Kanawha River. A geographical analysis of Cherokee resource abundance and constraints confirms that despite Kentucky’s distance from the core Cherokee settlements in the southern Blue Ridge, it was a valuable and efficient corridor for deer hunting throughout the eighteenth century (Gragson and Bolstad 2007b, Fig. 3).

Despite Cherokee claims, the southern Ohio River drainage was a contested hunting ground. The period of the 1720s to 1740s saw a reconsolidation of diasporic Shawnee bands along the north bank of the Ohio River between the Scioto and Allegheny Rivers, which had been largely vacant since the 1680s. The return of the Shawnees to the Ohio country led to conflict over Kentucky hunting grounds between the Shawnees and the Cherokee and Catawba (Lakomaki 2014, 43–60). Shawnee raiders even struck into the heart of Cherokee country, and vice versa, according to several traditions reported by Mooney (1975 [1900], 372–375).

Clearly, despite pretensions to a far-flung northern boundary that embraced much of modern-day Kentucky, the strength of the Cherokee claim decreased with each mile northward, especially after the reconsolidation of the Shawnees by midcentury. Evidence suggests that at least some Shawnee continued to linger in settlements in Kentucky for twenty years or more after the expulsion of the Cumberland River Shawnees. The Cumberland River itself may even have been re-settled by Shawnees before the American Revolution (Mahr 1960; Howard 1981, 6).

By the 1770s, the Shawnee and not the Cherokee were the leading defenders against white encroachment of the territory south of the Ohio. Lord Dunmore’s War of 1774 took place on lands recently relinquished by both the Haudenosaunee (1768) and the Cherokee (1768–1771) but still tenaciously defended by the Shawnee. Despite ceding title to these lands in the Treaty of Camp Charlotte following the war, the Shawnee continued as the principal native antagonists in the violence that consumed Kentucky during the American Revolution.

properties.name: Path from Fort Moore to the Congarees
properties.description:
The exact route of the historical trail between Savannah Town/Fort Moore and the Congarees is not known, but I have attempted to map its possible route given the available evidence.

The first map to show a trail between Savannah Town/Fort Moore and the Congarees is the 1721 Barnwell map. On this map, the route is pictured as a basically straight line but is shown to cross Town Creek and the South Fork of the Edisto River.

William P. Myer’s 1923 map of the Trail System of the Southeastern United States in the Early Colonial Period pictures this route as an extension of the Occaneechi Path, which runs between modern Petersburg, Virginia and Augusta, Georgia. Myer gives no written details about the South Carolina portion of this route, but the map shows a distinct bulge near the western end of this segment. This zig-zag in the route clearly follows the rim of the Edisto River watershed, which bypasses the numerous upper tributaries of the Edisto River’s north and south forks that intersect a more direct course between Savannah Town/Fort Moore and the Congarees.

In reconstructing the possible route, I have for the most part followed existing road beds along this ridge. In keeping with Barnwell’s map, the route makes two river crossings and avoids others. First, the route crosses Town Creek at a speculative location about six miles east of Fort Moore. Second, the route crosses Shaw’s Creek, a tributary of the South Fork Edisto River, before turning north and meeting with the main watershed divide. Either Barnwell left the crossing of Shaw’s Creek off of his map, or, as may be more likely, he considered what we now know as Shaw’s Creek to be the main headwaters of the South Fork.
